"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Periodic paralysis syndrome (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/periodic-paralysis-syndrome-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H544994173\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is periodic paralysis syndrome?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Periodic paralysis syndrome, called &ldquo;PP&rdquo; for short, is a rare condition that causes sudden episodes of muscle weakness. These episodes are brought on by certain things, such as:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Heavy exercise",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Eating a lot of carbohydrates &ndash; Carbohydrates are sugars and starches that are in food.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Stress",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Not eating for long periods of time",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Very cold air",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      There are different types of PP, depending on the cause. The different types are:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Hypokalemic PP &ndash; &ldquo;Hypokalemia&rdquo; is the medical term for low levels of potassium in the blood. Potassium is a salt that cells need to work normally. Too much or too little potassium can cause problems. Hypokalemic PP happens when there is too little potassium in the body.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Hyperkalemic PP &ndash; &ldquo;Hyperkalemia&rdquo; is the medical term for high levels of potassium in the blood. Hyperkalemic PP usually happens when there is too much potassium in the body.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Thyrotoxic PP &ndash; This is a type of hypokalemic PP, but it is caused by a condition called hyperthyroidism. In hyperthyroidism, a gland called the thyroid is overactive and makes too much thyroid hormone (",
"        <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef66834 \" href=\"mobipreview.htm?14/43/15024\">",
"         figure 1",
"        </a>",
"        ).",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Except in rare cases, people who have PP are born with it. The condition is caused by an abnormal gene and usually runs in families.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H544994211\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of periodic paralysis syndrome?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The symptoms depend partly on whether you have hypokalemic or hyperkalemic PP. In general, PP causes sudden episodes of muscle weakness that affect the whole body. These episodes do not make people pass out.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Hypokalemic PP episodes usually happen once every few weeks or months. Each episode usually lasts a few hours, but an episode can last for days.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Hyperkalemic PP episodes usually happen more often, sometimes every day. But each episode is not usually as severe and does not usually last as long.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Some patients with PP develop muscle weakness (that lasts all the time) later in life. These symptoms get worse slowly over time.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H544994226\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Will I need tests?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;It depends on whether the condition is known to run in your family. If the condition runs in your family, you probably won&rsquo;t need any tests.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If the condition isn&rsquo;t known to run in your family, your doctor will order tests. He or she will try to have the tests done when you are having symptoms. Tests that are commonly done include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Blood tests",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        An electrocardiogram (also called an &ldquo;ECG&rdquo; or &ldquo;EKG&rdquo;) &ndash; This test measures the electrical activity in your heart (",
"        <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef53145 \" href=\"mobipreview.htm?6/63/7154\">",
"         figure 2",
"        </a>",
"        ). Too little or too much potassium in the body can affect the heart.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Electromyography (also called &ldquo;EMG&rdquo;) &ndash; This test shows how well a person&rsquo;s nerves and muscles are working.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H544994264\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is periodic paralysis syndrome treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;PP is treated in different ways.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Some treatments can help stop or shorten episodes of muscle weakness. Hypokalemic PP episodes are treated with potassium that people take by mouth. This treatment helps raise the level of potassium in the body to a normal level.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Hyperkalemic PP episodes do not always need treatment, because they usually last for a short time only. But they are sometimes treated with medicines that lower the level of potassium in the body.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Other treatments can help prevent episodes of PP from happening. These include lifestyle changes and medicines.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Lifestyle changes that can help prevent episodes of PP include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Avoiding heavy exercise",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Eating a diet that is low in carbohydrates",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Avoiding foods with high levels of potassium, if you have hyperkalemic PP (",
"        <a class=\"graphic graphic_table graphicRef58250 \" href=\"mobipreview.htm?28/3/28732\">",
"         table 1",
"        </a>",
"        )",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If these lifestyle changes don&rsquo;t help enough, your doctor will talk with you about taking a daily medicine to help prevent symptoms. The medicine your doctor prescribes will depend on the type of PP you have.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H544994302\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What else should I do if I have periodic paralysis syndrome?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Be sure to let your other doctors and nurses know that you have this condition. That way, if you ever have a procedure or surgery, the doctor can make sure your potassium level doesn&rsquo;t get too low or too high.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H544994317\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       More on this topic",
"      </span>",
"     </p>",
